answers.body_markdown:
Actually, when you delete the second element the value for the third element is set again. So value watcher handler is executed. In your handler you try to set the value with jQuery:

```javaScript
watch: {
    value: function (value) {
      // update value
      $(this.$el).val(value)
    },...
```
But it doesn&#39;t work because this action doesn&#39;t fire `change` event. So Vue doesn&#39;t render any changes.

To fix it fire `change` event explicitly:

```javaScript
 watch: {
    value: function (value) {
      // update value
      $(this.$el).val(value).trigger(&#39;change&#39;)
    },...
``` 

I also noticed in your demo that your `select` elements are not initialized correctly. You pass:
```javaScript
mySelects: [
      {label: &#39;first&#39;, val: 1},
      {label: &#39;second&#39;, val: 2},
      {label: &#39;third&#39;, val: 3}
    ],...
```
So, in the first `select` value 1 must be selected, in the second - value 2, etc.

There are two steps to fix it:

1. trigger `change` event explicitly after you set the value
2. set the value after passing options

```javaScript
 mounted: function () {
    var vm = this
    $(this.$el)
    // first pass the options
      .select2({ data: this.options })
    // and then set the value
      .val(this.value)
    // trigger change event explicitly to let Vue know that it has to update DOM
      .trigger(&#39;change&#39;)
    // emit event on change.
      .on(&#39;change&#39;, function () {
        vm.$emit(&#39;input&#39;, this.value)
      })
  },
```

